\maketitle

Modelling the gravitational potential of the Milky Way has been an ever
evolving topic in recent decades. \texttt{Barros2016} provides a brief
history. Here the potential is used to approximate the force on the
simulated stars and to initialize field stars.

The model of choice consists of four parts: black hole, bulge, disc and
the dark matter halo.

The \textbf{black hole} is represented by a Keplerian potential:

\[\Phi_{bh}\left ( r \right ) = -\frac{G*M_{bh}}{r}\]

with \(r\) being the spherical radius.

The \textbf{disk} can be modelled via a Miyamoto Nagai potential
\texttt{1975PASJ..27..533M}

\[\Phi_{disk}\left ( R,z \right ) = -\frac{G*M_{disk}}{\sqrt{R^{2+\left ( a_{disk}+\sqrt{z^{2}+b_{disk}^{2}} \right )^{2}}}}\]\[\rho_{disk}(R,z)=\frac{b_{disk}^{2}M_{disk}}{4\pi}\frac{a_{disk}R^{2}+\left[a_{disk}+3(z^{2}+b_{disk}^{2})^{\frac{1}{2}}\right]\left[a_{disk}+(z^{2}+b_{disk}^{2})^{\frac{1}{2}}\right]^{2}}{\left \{ R^{2}+\left[a_{disk}+(z^{2}+b_{disk}^{2})^{\frac{1}{2}}\right]^{2} \right \}^{\frac{5}{2}}\left(z^{2}+b_{disk}^{2}\right)^{\frac{3}{2}}}\]

with \(R\) being the cylindrical radius and with \(z\) being the
distance to the reference plane.

For the \textbf{bulge} the Hernquist potential
\texttt{1990ApJ..356..359H} is used

\[\Phi_{bulge}\left ( r \right ) = -\frac{G*M_{bulge}}{\left ( r+a_{bulge} \right )}\]\[\rho_{bulge}(r)= \frac{M_{bulge}}{2\pi }\frac{a_{bulge}}{r}\frac{1}{\left ( r+a_{bulge} \right )^{3}}\]

\(a\) being the scale-length of the spheroid potential

and the NFW potential \texttt{Navarro1996} is used for the \textbf{dark
matter halo} potential

\[\Phi_{halo}\left ( r \right ) = \frac{-4\pi G\rho _{s}r_{s}^{3}\ln\left ( 1+\frac{r}{r_{s}}\right )}{r}\]

where \(\rho _{s}\) is the characteristic density and \(r_{s}\) the
scale length.

Parameters for bulge and disk taken from \texttt{Price\_Whelan\_2014}
and the radius \(r_{s}\) for the halo from \texttt{Bovy\_2015}:

