\hypertarget{angular-velocity}{%
\section{Angular Velocity}\label{angular-velocity}}

The angular velocity is required for initializing disc star velocities
and can be obtained from the potential:

\[\Omega ^{2}\left ( R \right ) = \frac{1}{R}\frac{\partial \Phi \left ( R,0 \right )}{\partial r}\]

For the total potential \texttt{total\_potential} this derivation
yields:

\[\Omega ^{2}\left ( R \right ) = \frac{G}{R} \left\{-\frac{M_{bulge}}{(a_{bulge}+R)^2}+\frac{2 M_{disk} R^3}{\left[\left(a_{disk}+b_{disk}\right)^2+R^4\right]^{1.5}}+\frac{M_{bh}}{R^2}-\frac{4 \pi  p_{s} r_{s}^3}{R^2+R r_{s}}+\frac{4 \pi  p_{s} r_{s}^3 \ln \left(\frac{R+r_{s}}{r_{s}}\right)}{R^2}\right\}\]

\hypertarget{mass-distribution}{%
\section{Mass Distribution}\label{mass-distribution}}

The mass inside a volume is calculated by numerical integration of the
density. GSL implementation of Monte Carlo Integration is used. For
further details refer to the GSL
\href{https://www.gnu.org/software/gsl/doc/html/montecarlo.html}{documentation}.

